&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;strong&gt;India embarks on planned economic development&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;India embarked on planned economic development in 1950 with the launch of the First Five-Year Plan. The goal of planned economic development was to rapidly industrialise the country and to improve the lives of its citizens.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;India faces balances of payment crisis pledges gold to shore up reserves&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;India faced a balances of payment crisis in 1991. The crisis was caused by a number of factors, including a decline in exports and an increase in imports. The Government of India pledged gold to the International Monetary Fund in order to shore up its reserves and to meet its foreign debt obligations.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The correct answer is &amp;quot;Commercial paper.&amp;quot;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&amp;nbsp;M1 refers to a measure of the money supply &lt;/strong&gt;that includes highly liquid assets that can be readily used for transactions. The components of M1 typically include:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Currency: Physical cash in circulation, including coins and banknotes.&lt;br /&gt;
Demand deposits: Funds held in checking accounts and other types of accounts that can be withdrawn on demand by the depositor, typically through checks, debit cards, or electronic transfers.&lt;br /&gt;
Travelers&amp;#39; checks: These are prepaid checks that are widely accepted by merchants and banks and can be exchanged for local currency while traveling.&lt;br /&gt;
&amp;quot;Commercial paper&amp;quot; refers to short-term debt instruments issued by corporations and financial institutions to raise funds for short-term financing needs. While commercial paper is an important financial instrument, it is not considered a component of M1 because it is not directly used for transactions by households and businesses in the same way as currency, demand deposits, and travelers&amp;#39; checks. Commercial paper falls under the category of M2 or M3, broader measures of the money supply that include less liquid assets.&lt;/p&gt;

